				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sharpembrace" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6032914); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6032914&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610200957" alt="SharpEmbrace" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6032914)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/sharpembrace" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6032914); return false;" >SharpEmbrace</a></span> <span class="odate time_1588027327 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Apr 2020 22:42</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4617778">
									

<p>Downvoting, but I applaud you for trying something different stylistically. I think minimalist, short-form works are some of the hardest things to write successfully, so I'm not really surprised this flopped a bit. I find that the key things for works like those is implication. You need to show the reader more than just the words and pictures on the page. This can be difficult to do but is amazing when done well, as letting your readers discover the story with less hand-holding can be really powerful. It is one thing to push the audience into a sombre wasteland; it is another thing entirely to let them wander it alone and find the sad truth of what caused it. That said, there's very little implication of what caused the bombs to be dropped. A nuclear war happened, presumably, but beyond that I have nothing. It's so vague that it ends up lacking any real effect on me. Additionally, what we <em>do</em> have doesn't build a sense of profound loss that makes the seeds of hope a powerful image for me. Overall, this ended up being a disappointing story.</p>

							</div>

